# Building a credential injection proxy for AWS

Credential injection proxies (e.g. [OneCLI](https://www.onecli.sh), [AgentVault](https://github.com/Infisical/agent-vault), [tokenizer](https://github.com/superfly/tokenizer)) are a cool idea: rather than giving third-party secrets to workloads, you hold them in a proxy that injects them into traffic. They're a good fit for AI agents too, because data exfiltration threats like prompt injection are limited to (hopefully less useful) internal proxy credentials, as opposed to powerful API tokens. Keeping the credential out of context entirely is better than hoping the agent doesn't leak it. The setup looks roughly like: 

- The agent gets a low-privilege bearer token that authenticates _it_ to the proxy and trusts the proxy's CA cert so HTTPS traffic can be intercepted.
- From there the agent goes about its business: it sets `HTTPS_PROXY`, makes normal HTTP calls with placeholder keys
- The proxy swaps those for real third-party credentials at request time.

```python
# Header-swap proxy, the entire idea
def request(self, flow):
    if flow.request.headers.get("Authorization") == "Bearer FAKE_TOKEN":
        flow.request.headers["Authorization"] = "Bearer " + real_token_from_vault()
```


Where this cool idea doesn't work out of the box is with AWS access keys, where requests are signed rather than authenticated with a static token. The SigV4 signature is bound to the request body, the host, the timestamp, and the headers themselves. You can't inject a credential after the fact; you have to recompute the signature. Also, AWS credentials are usually dynamic, resolved at request time through a chain of providers. That means an AWS-aware credential injection proxy needs to do two things the existing tools don't combine: vend AWS credentials dynamically, and re-sign the request on its way out.

This post is a proof of concept for that combination. The implementation is a Python mitmproxy addon that strips the existing signing headers and recomputes them using credentials from an elhaz config. As I was building this, I realized the upside isn't just credential isolation. Once the proxy is the signer, you get per-call session policies, per-call audit, and per-call deny. There's something powerful about this concept that's worth exploring further.

## Existing approaches

There's a small ecosystem of AWS-aware proxies. AWS publishes [aws-sigv4-proxy](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-sigv4-proxy). Envoy ships an [aws_request_signing HTTP filter](https://www.envoyproxy.io/docs/envoy/latest/configuration/http/http_filters/aws_request_signing_filter). Backstage has a sigv4 plugin. They're variants of the same idea: the caller sends an unsigned request and the proxy adds the signature on the way out. That works for curl scripts, custom HTTP clients, and frontends like Backstage. It does not work for the AWS CLI or any AWS SDK, which sign before they hit the network. By the time a request from `aws s3 cp` reaches the proxy, it's already signed, with whatever placeholder credentials were in the agent's environment. The proxy can't just sign it; it has to strip the placeholder signature and re-sign with credentials of its own.

There's also AWS's [mcp-proxy-for-aws](https://github.com/aws/mcp-proxy-for-aws), which signs MCP traffic with SigV4 so MCP clients like Claude Desktop can talk to IAM-secured MCP servers on AWS. It's solving a different problem — bridging MCP transport to IAM auth, not isolating credentials from the agent — and it pulls AWS credentials from the standard credential chain on the same machine the agent runs on. If credential isolation is what you're after, it doesn't help: the agent process can just read the same credentials directly.

_(GCP and Azure have similar dynamics. GCP's request signing for service account keys and Azure's Shared Key authentication both bind credentials into the request in ways header swap can't handle. The AWS case is the one I'm digging into here, but the pattern generalizes. Anywhere request signing exists, the credential-injection proxy needs the same two-step shape.)_

## The fix: strip and re-sign

The implementation is a [mitmproxy](https://mitmproxy.org/) addon. mitmproxy intercepts HTTPS by terminating TLS at the proxy with its own CA cert, which the agent has to trust. Once the request is in plaintext, the addon strips the existing SigV4 headers and re-signs using credentials it fetches from a vault. botocore does the actual signing math.

```python
def request(self, flow):
    if not is_aws_host(flow.request.pretty_host):
        return

    # Strip the placeholder signature
    for h in ["authorization", "x-amz-date", "x-amz-security-token", "x-amz-content-sha256"]:
        del flow.request.headers[h]

    # Re-sign with credentials the agent doesn't hold
    creds = self.cache.get()
    aws_request = AWSRequest(method=..., url=..., data=..., headers=...)
    SigV4Auth(creds, service, region).add_auth(aws_request)

    for key, value in aws_request.headers.items():
        flow.request.headers[key] = value
```

The credential resolution side is whatever you want it to be. I used [elhaz](https://github.com/61418/elhaz), the local credential daemon I built for the [previous post](https://engseclabs.com/blog/agent-credential-isolation/), because it was already on my laptop and it vends short-lived credentials for a named role over a Unix socket. aws-vault would work. A `credential_process` entry would work. Anything that produces fresh AWS credentials would work. The proxy doesn't care where they come from, only that they exist when it needs to sign.

The agent still has to ship _something_ in `AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID` and `AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY`. The SDK and CLI won't build a request at all without credentials in the environment, so the agent has to think it has some. The proxy strips those headers entirely and re-signs, so the placeholders never reach AWS. They're inert: they have to exist for the SDK to proceed, but they can't authenticate anything outside the proxy. This is honestly a small wart on the credential-injection model when applied to AWS; OneCLI has the same constraint with its placeholder API keys.

The hostname parsing is the part with the most surface area, because AWS endpoints encode the service and region differently across services and regions:

|Host|Service|Region|
|---|---|---|
|`sts.amazonaws.com`|sts|us-east-1 (global endpoint)|
|`s3.amazonaws.com`|s3|us-east-1 (global endpoint)|
|`s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com`|s3|us-west-2|
|`ec2.eu-west-1.amazonaws.com`|ec2|eu-west-1|
|`my-bucket.s3.amazonaws.com`|s3|us-east-1 (virtual-hosted)|
|`my-bucket.s3.ap-southeast-1.amazonaws.com`|s3|ap-southeast-1|

Global endpoints have to be matched before the catch-all `<service>.amazonaws.com` pattern. Virtual-hosted S3 buckets need their own cases since the bucket name prefix would otherwise look like a service name. The full addon is in the [repo](https://github.com/61418/elhaz/blob/main/poc/elhaz_resign.py) along with setup instructions.

Test call:

```
$ aws sts get-caller-identity
{
    "UserId": "AROAUB266OVZPC3ZFTYIY:boto3-refresh-session",
    "Arn": "arn:aws:sts::278835131762:assumed-role/RoleChaining1/boto3-refresh-session"
}
```

The returned ARN is the role the proxy is configured to use, not the placeholder identity in the agent's environment.

## What this gets you beyond credential isolation

Once the proxy is the signer, it can do things the agent can't undo.

The most interesting one is per-call session policies. When the proxy resolves credentials for a given outbound request, it can call `AssumeRole` with an inline session policy scoped to that specific call (read-only, or limited to a single bucket prefix, or limited to a single API action) and sign with the resulting short-lived credentials. The role the agent thinks it has is `RoleX`. The credentials AWS actually sees are `RoleX intersected with whatever policy the proxy attached to this call`. The agent has no way to broaden the scope back out, because it has no signing material and never sees the scoped credentials. This changes the unit of authorization from "what role is the agent allowed to use" to "what role is the agent allowed to use, for this specific request." It's hard to get this property any other way. An agent that holds long-lived role credentials can always call `AssumeRole` itself with whatever policy it wants. An agent that talks through the proxy can only act with the credentials the proxy chose to mint.

The proxy also sees every request in plaintext before it goes to AWS. CloudTrail tells you what AWS authorized after the fact. The proxy can tell you what the agent tried to do, including the calls that the proxy itself denied, which never reach CloudTrail at all. That gap matters when you're trying to baseline agent behavior or catch prompt-injection attempts that asked for things the agent shouldn't have asked for in the first place.

And the proxy is a natural place to enforce per-call policy that doesn't fit cleanly into IAM. Rate limits per agent, time-of-day restrictions, blocks on specific request shapes, allow-lists scoped by tag: all things you can express in a proxy in fifty lines, and all things that take significantly more infrastructure to express in IAM. None of it requires the proxy to be the signer, but the same surface that's already inspecting and re-signing requests is the cheapest place to put it.

## Honest constraints

This whole thing is a proof of concept, not a tool. The point of writing it was to show that the strip-and-resign pattern works and to give it enough shape that someone building a real credential-injection proxy can lift the idea. The hostname-parsing table, the strip-then-`SigV4Auth` flow, the AWS-CLI-insists-on-signing constraint: these are the conceptual building blocks. The mitmproxy Python addon is the cheapest possible vehicle for them. There are SigV4 edge cases the addon doesn't handle: SigV4a for multi-region access points, streaming payload signing for large S3 uploads, and response inspection. None of them are conceptually hard, just not built.

